3D Superresolution¶

In order to improve the accuracy of segmentation algorithms and interpretability of SBF-SEM datasets, we perform 3D axial superresolution.

One of the practical concerns with the major breakthroughs in deep superresolution is that the networks require ground truth volumes or images to train the network. However, because of the limits of our imaging modalities, we cannot obtain volumetric samples without axial decimation. However, the advantage of SBF-SEM is high resolution in the lateral plane.

The network used in a modification of the original superresolution network from Dong et al. (2051). Instead of using 2D convolutional layers, we use 3D convolutional layers. Furthermore, we perform superresolution only along a single axis, whereas the 2D SRCNN and the rest of the deep superresolution models perform superresolution along both x and y axis.

We used the ADAM optimizer with a learning rate of 1e^-3 to train the network. We use relu activation functions throughout the entire network. During training, we took 1x800x800 px samples of our training platelet dataset, and preformed un-filtered decimation to produce 1x200x800 samples to form training-test pairs. We then upsampled the training set via bicubic interpolation (as per Dong et.al) to yield a 1x800x800 volume which we then feed through the network.

To perform inference and generate an isotropic volume, we first transpose our inference set to yield a volume of shape 800x50x800, from which we take 1x50x800 samples from, perform bicubic interpolation to generate a 1x200x800 images. We then use these as inputs to the network, and then reconstruct and transpose the output to yield a final, isotropic volume of shape 200x800x800.

We trained the network to minimize a mean squared error objective function, equivalent to maximizing peak signal-to-noise ratio (PSNR)

Quantitative Results¶

In order to benchmark the performance of the 3D SRCNN on the platelet dataset, we also perform 3D superresolution via the three most common non-neural techniques: nearest neighbours, bilinear and bicubic interpolation.

def spline_interp(order, fpath, scale):

    vol_interp = []
    for f in sort_alphanumeric(os.listdir(fpath)):

        block = tif.imread(os.path.join(fpath, f))
        block_interp = scipy.ndimage.zoom(block, (1, scale, 1), order=order)
        vol_interp.append(block_interp)

    vol_interp = np.array(vol_interp)
    vol_interp = np.squeeze(vol_interp)

    return vol_interp

# using the decimated training set to compute baseline metrics
traindir_data = os.path.join(traindir, "train")
neighbours = spline_interp(0, traindir_data, 4)
bilinear = spline_interp(1, traindir_data, 4)
bicubic = spline_interp(3, traindir_data, 4)
srcnn_fpath = os.path.join(datapath, "outputs/srcnn_train.tif")
srcnn = tif.imread(srcnn_fpath)

psnr_nn = psnr(test_volume, neighbours)
psnr_lin = psnr(test_volume, bilinear)
psnr_cub = psnr(test_volume, bicubic)
psnr_srcnn = psnr(test_volume, srcnn)

print("Nearest Neighbours: %.2f dB" % (psnr_nn,))
print("Linear Interpolation: %.2f dB" %(psnr_lin,))
print("Bicubic Interpolation: %.2f dB"%(psnr_cub,))
print("3D SRCNN: %.2f dB" % (psnr_srcnn,))

The 3D SRNN far outperforms the non-neural methods in terms of PSNR. In order to determine exactly where the 3D SRNN had it's advantages, we used a windowed PSNR metric, and determined that the SRCNN yieled a performance increase in regions that contained more dense cellular structures.

def window(data, blck, strd):
    sh = np.array(data.shape)
    blck = np.asanyarray(blck)
    strd = np.asanyarray(strd)
    nbl = (sh - blck) // strd + 1
    strides = np.r_[data.strides * strd, data.strides]
    dims = np.r_[nbl, blck]
    windows = np.lib.stride_tricks.as_strided(data, strides=strides, shape=dims)
    return windows


def windowed_psnr(vol_true, vol_test, window_size, stride):

    windows_true = window(vol_true, window_size, stride)
    windows_true = np.squeeze(windows_true)
    windows_test = window(vol_test, window_size, stride)
    windows_test = np.squeeze(windows_test)
    x = windows_test.shape[0]
    y = windows_test.shape[1]
    windowed_psnr = np.zeros((x, y))
    for ii in range(0, x):
        for jj in range(0, y):
            patch_true = windows_true[ii, jj, :, :, :]
            patch_test = windows_test[ii, jj, :, :, :]
            windowed_psnr[ii, jj] = psnr(patch_true, patch_test)

    return windowed_psnr

win_size = (10, 200, 200)
stride = 50
psnr_nn_windowed = windowed_psnr(test_volume, neighbours, win_size, stride)
psnr_lin_windowed = windowed_psnr(test_volume, bilinear, win_size, stride)
psnr_cub_windowed = windowed_psnr(test_volume, bicubic, win_size, stride)
psnr_srcnn_windowed = windowed_psnr(test_volume, srcnn, win_size, stride)

nn_comparison = (psnr_srcnn_windowed - psnr_nn_windowed) > 0.1
lin_comparison = (psnr_srcnn_windowed - psnr_lin_windowed) > 0.1
cub_comparison = (psnr_srcnn_windowed - psnr_cub_windowed) > 0.1
